{'contentformat': 'text/x-wiki', 'contentmodel': 'wikitext', '*': '{{PokémonPrevNext/Head|type=Ground|type2=Psychic}}\n{{PokémonPrevNext/GO|species=Baltoy}}\n{{PokémonPrevNext/Pokémon|type=Ground|prevnum=342|prev=Crawdaunt|nextnum=344|next=Claydol|roundleft=bl|roundright=br}}\n|}\n{{Pokémon Infobox\n|name=Baltoy\n|jname=ヤジロン\n|jtranslit=Yajiron\n|tmname=Yajilon\n|ndex=343\n|hdex=131\n|hdex6=136\n|u2dex=169\n|obrow=173\n|opbrow=165\n|typebox=1\n|type1=Ground\n|type2=Psychic\n|category=Clay Doll\n|height-ftin=1\'08"\n|height-m=0.5\n|weight-lbs=47.4\n|weight-kg=21.5\n|abilityn=1\n|abilitylayout=1\n|ability1=Levitate\n|egggroupn=1\n|egggroup1=Mineral\n|eggcycles=20\n|evtotal=1\n|evsd=1\n|expyield=60\n|oldexp=58\n|lv100exp=1,000,000\n|gendercode=255\n|color=Brown\n|catchrate=255\n|body=04\n|pokefordex=baltoy\n|generation=3\n|friendship=70\n}}\n\'\'\'Baltoy\'\'\' ([[List of Japanese Pokémon names|Japanese]]: \'\'\'ヤジロン\'\'\' \'\'Yajilon\'\') is a dual-type {{2t|Ground|Psychic}} {{OBP|Pokémon|species}} introduced in [[Generation III]].\n\nIt [[Evolution|evolve]]s into {{p|Claydol}} starting at [[level]] 36.\n\n==Biology==\nBaltoy is a small Pokémon that resembles a tan figurine made out of clay or mud. There are arching, red markings over its eyes, which usually appear closed. A red stripe encircles its body, and forms a ring on its belly. It has flat appendages that resemble arms. A spike protrudes from the top of its head and another, smaller spike under its body. It moves by spinning on this single, pointed foot, and balance upright on it to sleep. Baltoy is usually found in {{DL|List of Pokémon by habitat|Rough-terrain Pokémon|ruins}} and old graveyards, where it congregates with its own kind and cries noisily. Old cave wall paintings depict it living with people in ancient times.\n\n==In the anime==\n[[File:Buck Baltoy.png|thumb|250px|left|Baltoy in the {{pkmn|anime}}]]\n===Major appearances===\nBaltoy debuted in \'\'[[AG076|Me, Myself and Time]]\'\', under the ownership of {{OBP|Calista|AG076}}. It was first seen spinning around and heading off a cliff, being saved by {{AP|Pikachu}}’s {{m|Quick Attack}}. Later, it helped its future self by removing the rocks that were crushing it. It then used {{m|Rapid Spin}} in the middle of a wheel of drawings to reveal the true identity of a mysterious woman, who was actually a future Calista.\n\nIn \'\'[[AG099|It\'s Still Rocket Roll to Me!]]\'\', [[Tate and Liza]] were using the {{m|Confusion}} created by four Baltoy to recreate weightlessness during a Pokémon battle, even though their main Pokémon already possessed the ability to float in midair. Later, these Clay Doll Pokémon stopped {{TRT}} from stealing a rocket ship with Tate and [[Max]] in tow.\n\nFour Baltoy appeared in \'\'[[M12|Arceus and the Jewel of Life]]\'\', under the ownership of [[Damos]]. In the original timeline set up by the movie, they were used by Damos, who was under {{m|Hypnosis}}, to attack {{OBP|Arceus|M12}} with {{m|Shock Wave}}. When Ash and {{ashfr}} traveled to the past to prevent this, [[Marcus]], the one responsible for hypnotizing Damos, managed to use the Baltoy again to attack Arceus.\n\nA Baltoy appeared in \'\'[[DP181|Bucking the Treasure Trend!]]\'\', under the ownership of [[Buck]]. It was Buck\'s main Pokémon and partner in treasure-hunting, having the ability to sense when treasure is near. It would indicate this to Buck by spinning. Baltoy was also a very powerful battler, as it was able to defeat the Claydol that was guarding the treasure hidden near [[Lily of the Valley Island]].\n\n===Minor appearances===\nA Baltoy appeared in \'\'[[DP126|Classroom Training!]]\'\', under the ownership of the {{ci|Snowpoint}} {{pkmn|Trainers\' School}}.\n\n===Pokédex entries===\n{{Animedexheader|Hoenn}}\n{{Animedexbody|AG076|Baltoy|Ash\'s Pokédex|Baltoy, the Clay Doll Pokémon. Baltoy moves about while {{m|Rapid Spin|spinning like a top}}. It is said that Baltoy coexisted with humans in [[History of the Pokémon world|ancient times]].}}\n{{Animedexfooter/Pokémon|\'\'Advanced Generation\'\'|Hoenn}}\n{{Animedexheader|Sinnoh}}\n{{Animedexbody|DP181|Baltoy|Dawn\'s Pokédex|Baltoy, the Clay Doll Pokémon. A rarely seen Pokémon, Baltoy is said to have been discovered in an ancient ruin.}}\n{{Animedexfooter/Pokémon|\'\'Diamond & Pearl\'\'|Sinnoh}}\n\n==In the manga==\n[[File:Baltoy Adventures.png|thumb|200px|Baltoy in [[Pokémon Adventures]]]]\n===In the Ash & Pikachu manga===\nLike her anime counterpart, {{OBP|Calista|AG076}} owns a Baltoy. It appeared in \'\'[[SP26|Hunt For The Treasure Of The Universe!]]\'\'.\n\n===In the movie adaptations===\nIn the manga adaptation of {{ma|Arceus and the Jewel of Life}}, [[Marcus]] owns a Baltoy.\n\n===In the Pokémon Adventures manga===\nA Baltoy appeared in \'\'[[PS241|Dreadful Dealing with Dusclops]]\'\', where it attacked {{adv|Wally}} inside the [[Sky Pillar]].\n\nA {{tc|Worker}}\'s Baltoy appeared in [[PS546]].\n\n==In the TCG==\n{{main|Baltoy (TCG)}}\n\n==Game data==\n===Pokédex entries===\n{{Dex/Header|type=Ground|type2=Psychic}}\n{{Dex/NA|gen=III}}\n{{Dex/Gen/2|gen=III|reg1=Hoenn|num1=131|reg2=Kanto}}\n{{Dex/Entry1|v=Ruby|t=FFF|entry=Baltoy moves while {{m|Rapid Spin|spinning}} around on its one foot. Primitive wall paintings depicting this Pokémon living among people were discovered in some ancient ruins.}}\n{{Dex/Entry1|v=Sapphire|t=FFF|entry=As soon as it spots others of its kind, Baltoy congregates with them and then begins crying noisily in unison. This Pokémon sleeps while cleverly balancing itself on its one foot.}}\n{{Dex/Entry1|v=Emerald|t=FFF|entry=A Baltoy moves by spinning on its single foot. It has been depicted in murals adorning the walls of a once-bustling city in an ancient age.}}\n{{Dex/Entry2|v=FireRed|v2=LeafGreen|entry=It was discovered in ancient ruins. While moving, it constantly spins. It stands on one foot even when asleep.}}\n|}\n|}\n{{Dex/Gen/2|gen=IV|reg1=Sinnoh|reg2=Johto}}\n{{Dex/Entry3|v=Diamond|v2=Pearl|v3=P